g.title: Folded Corner.205
g.desc: The Interpreter pattern compliments the Single Responsibility...

g.text: The Interpreter pattern compliments the Single Responsibility Principle by expressing each Grammar rule in a separate class. A Grammar rule is called an Expression. The Parser (=client) can compose these expressions in an tree-like structure (=AST). After parsing, interpretation of the AST takes place. The result of this interpretation is a different representation or action. The client (=Parser) and Grammar are separated from each other. The Interpreter pattern enhances reusability, testability, stability, flexibility and maintainability. All aspects are compared against an implementation where all Grammar rules (=Expressions) are defined in centralized place (e.g.: single class or function). Reusability, because different Parsers can re-use different parts of the Grammar instead of being dependent on the full Grammar directly and new Grammar rules can inherit from existing ones. Testability, because each Expression of the Grammar can be tested in isolation. This ‘shrinks’ the problem window compared to having the Expressions into a single place. Stability, because the impact of changing a grammar rule is minimized. In contrast, expressing the full Grammar in a single place (class) might endanger breaking other Expressions unrelated to the change. Flexibility, because an expression can be queued for interpretation. (E.g. waiting until another expression is interpreted). Maintainability, each grammar rule defines its own class, enabling ‘shrinkage’ of the problem window. This enables identifying problems faster, but also enhances readability.

g.title: Folded Corner.216
g.desc: The Interpreter pattern is most appropriate in case the langu...

g.text: The Interpreter pattern is most appropriate in case the language does not define an extensive Grammar. Using the Interpreter pattern for extensive Grammars can become complex and unmanageable, because we need to define each Grammar rule and construct ASTs from it. In case of an extensive Grammar it might be more appropriate to switch to a Parser generator. A Parser generator can be seen as a ‘Parser Parser’. The Grammar can be specified via a more abstract language and will be interpreted by a parser into another Parser. The generated Parser can construct a parse tree based on our Grammar definition. This parse tree can be interpreted and generates a different representation.

g.title: Folded Corner.196
g.desc: The Interpreter violates the Single Responsibility Principle....

g.text: The Interpreter violates the Single Responsibility Principle. The growth in size and complexity of a Grammar can ensure a class ‘explosion’. This is caused by specifying each Grammar rule as a separate class. This results in a scattered code base that becomes hard to maintain and navigate through. Parser generators can be used as a resolution for extensive grammars.

g.title: Folded Corner.235
g.desc: The purpose of the Interpreter pattern is to evaluate sentenc...

g.text: The purpose of the Interpreter pattern is to evaluate sentences in a language and interpreting it into another more sophisticated one. The pattern distinguishes between terminal and non-terminal symbols. Terminal symbols are the symbols that form the base of a language. A terminal symbol is a also called a ‘Leave’. Non-terminal symbols merge Terminal and Non-Terminal symbols. A Non-Terminal symbol is a Composite. E.g. in the mathematical expression: 1+2. ‘1’ and ‘2’ are terminal. The ‘+’ is Non-Terminal. A Grammar is defined by Non-Terminal and Terminal Symbols (=Lexical elements). The Interpreter pattern specifies an object for each Terminal and Non-Terminal symbol. An Abstract Syntax Tree (=AST) can be composed from these Lexical elements. The Interpreter is used to evaluate/Interpret the AST based on a given Context. The Interpreter pattern doesn’t express how to parse the Lexical input into an AST.

g.title: Folded Corner.247
g.desc: The Interpreter pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle...

g.text: The Interpreter pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle. The Open Closed principle is supported by the Dependency Inversion Principle. Each Expression in the Interpreter pattern implements and/or is dependent on an abstraction. This contributes to the stability of the code base. All aspects are compared against an implementation where all Grammar rules (=Expressions) are defined in centralized place (e.g.: single class or function). Stability, because newly introduced Expressions can be injected into existing Non Terminal Expressions without direct modification. This enables production and test code stability. In contrast, introducing a new Expression where the Grammar is defined in a centralized place, would most probably result in changing existing logic.

g.title: Folded Corner.251
g.desc: The Interpreter pattern expresses parse trees often in the fo...

g.text: The Interpreter pattern expresses parse trees often in the form of an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST). However, this might not always be the most ‘efficient’ form for interpretation. This form is ‘strongly’ dependent on the problem domain. E.g. a Regular Expression Matcher, that interprets an input string based on a given string pattern into a Boolean, might be best expressed in the form of an FSA (Finite State Automata). The interpretation, by expressing the regular expression in a FSA, might be significantly faster then an AST .In this particular problem domain, interpretation might result in exponential time for ASTs and linear time for FSAs .
